### Vulnerability 1 — OpenWire Protocol: Arbitrary Throwable Class Loading (CRITICAL)
**Files:**
- `activemq-client/src/main/java/org/apache/activemq/openwire/v1-v12/BaseDataStreamMarshaller.java` (all 12 versions)
- `activemq-openwire-legacy/src/main/java/org/apache/activemq/openwire/v2-v8/BaseDataStreamMarshaller.java`
**Vulnerable code (v12 representative, line 230–239):**
```java
private Throwable createThrowable(String className, String message) {
try {
className = convertJmsPackage(className);
Class clazz = Class.forName(className, false,    // <-- line 233
BaseDataStreamMarshaller.class.getClassLoader());
OpenWireUtil.validateIsThrowable(clazz);         // only checks Throwable subclass
Constructor constructor = clazz.getConstructor(new Class[] {String.class});
return (Throwable)constructor.newInstance(new Object[] {message});
} ...
}
```
**Data flow:**
1. A remote client sends an OpenWire protocol frame containing an exception payload.
2. `tightUnmarsalThrowable()` / `looseUnmarsalThrowable()` (lines 190–228 / 517–548) read `clazz` and `message` directly from the untrusted network stream.
3. `clazz` (fully user-controlled) is passed into `Class.forName()` at line 233.
4. The only guard — `validateIsThrowable()` — only checks that the loaded class extends `Throwable`; it does **not** restrict which class is loaded.
5. A specially crafted class that is a `Throwable` subclass and performs malicious actions in its `String`-arg constructor or static initializer will be instantiated with the attacker-supplied `message` string.
**Why it matters:** An attacker can place a malicious JAR on the classpath (common in enterprise deployments) and trigger its constructor via this path. Static initializers run at `Class.forName()` time even before `validateIsThrowable()` is called. Both the `tight` and `loose` encoding paths are affected."
